column3: A universal hashing scheme is a randomized algorithm that selects a hashing function h among a family of such functions, in such a way that the probability of a collision of any two distinct keys is 1 n, where n is the number of distinct hash values desired independently of the two keys.
Universal hashing ensures that the hash function application will behave as well as if it were using a random function, for any distribution of the input data.
